#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""
Git stacked branches management tool.

Supported commands:
  git stack ls|list                # List stacked branches and their status
  git stack create <branch>        # Create a new stacked branch from current branch
  git stack adopt <branch> [base]  # Tag existing branch as stacked on base (default: current branch)
  git stack set-parent <base>      # Set the parent/base of the current branch
  git stack base [new-base]        # Show or change the base of current stacked branch
  git stack sync1                  # Sync current branch with its immediate upstream
  git stack sync-up                # Sync current branch with all its upstreams (recursive)
  git stack sync-deps              # Sync dependants (descendants) of the current branch
  git stack sync-all               # Sync all stacked branches in the repository
  git stack continue               # Continue sync after resolving conflicts
  git stack abort                  # Abort current rebase, continue with remaining branches
  git stack abort-all              # Abort and restore all branches to original state
  git stack push                   # Push current stacked branch to remote
  git stack push-all               # Push all stacked branches to remote
  git stack push-remotes           # Push only branches that have remote tracking
  git stack delete <branch>        # Delete a stacked branch and update dependents
  git stack rename [<old>] <new>   # Rename a stacked branch and update all references
  git stack rebase <new-base>      # Rebase current stack onto a new base
  git stack log                    # Show log of commits in current stack
  git stack diff                   # Show diff of current branch against its base

Supported workflows:

============================================================================
USER JOURNEY 1: Creating a New Feature Stack
============================================================================
Start from main branch and create a series of dependent changes:

  $ git checkout main
  $ git stack create feature/step1
  # ... make changes for step 1 ...
  $ git commit -m "Step 1: Add base infrastructure"

  $ git stack create feature/step2     # Creates step2 stacked on step1
  # ... make changes for step 2 ...
  $ git commit -m "Step 2: Add API layer"

  $ git stack create feature/step3     # Creates step3 stacked on step2
  # ... make changes for step 3 ...
  $ git commit -m "Step 3: Add UI components"

Result: main <- feature/step1 <- feature/step2 <- feature/step3

============================================================================
USER JOURNEY 2: Adopting Existing Branches into a Stack
============================================================================
You have existing branches that you want to organize as a stack:

  $ git checkout feature/api-refactor
  $ git stack adopt feature/api-refactor main
  # Now feature/api-refactor is marked as stacked on main

  $ git checkout feature/api-tests
  $ git stack adopt feature/api-tests feature/api-refactor
  # Now feature/api-tests is marked as stacked on feature/api-refactor

Alternative (adopt current branch):
  $ git checkout feature/api-tests
  $ git stack adopt . feature/api-refactor

============================================================================
USER JOURNEY 3: Syncing After Upstream Changes
============================================================================
When main branch or a base branch gets updated:

Scenario A: Update just the current branch from its immediate parent:
  $ git checkout feature/step2
  $ git stack sync1
  # Rebases step2 onto the latest step1

Scenario B: Recursively sync current branch (sync all ancestors first):
  $ git checkout feature/step3
  $ git stack sync-up
  # First syncs step1 onto main, then step2 onto step1, then step3 onto step2

Scenario C: Sync only the dependants (not the current branch):
  $ git checkout feature/step1
  $ git stack sync-deps
  # Syncs step2 and step3, but leaves step1 as-is

Scenario D: Sync all stacked branches in the repo:
  $ git stack sync-all
  # Finds all stacked branches and syncs them in dependency order

============================================================================
USER JOURNEY 4: Nested Stacks (Stack on Stack)
============================================================================
Create a sub-feature that branches off another stacked branch:

  $ git checkout feature/step2
  $ git stack create feature/step2-hotfix
  # ... make hotfix changes ...
  $ git commit -m "Hotfix for step 2"

Result: main <- step1 <- step2 <- step2-hotfix
                             \\<- step3

Both step2-hotfix and step3 are based on step2. When step2 is updated:
  $ git checkout feature/step2
  # ... make changes ...
  $ git commit -m "Update step 2"
  $ git stack sync-all
  # Both step2-hotfix and step3 get rebased onto the new step2

============================================================================
USER JOURNEY 5: Changing the Base of a Stack
============================================================================
Move a stacked branch to a different base:

  $ git checkout feature/step3
  $ git stack base
  # Shows: feature/step2

  $ git stack base feature/step1
  # Rebases step3 onto step1 instead of step2

  $ git stack rebase main
  # Rebases step3 directly onto main, removing it from the stack

============================================================================
USER JOURNEY 6: Reviewing and Pushing Stacks
============================================================================
View the current stack structure:
  $ git stack ls
  # Output:
  #   main
  #   └── feature/step1 (2 commits ahead)
  #       └── feature/step2 (1 commit ahead)
  #           ├── feature/step2-hotfix (1 commit ahead)
  #           └── feature/step3 (3 commits ahead)

View commits in the current stacked branch:
  $ git checkout feature/step2
  $ git stack log
  # Shows commits in step2 that are not in step1

View diff against base:
  $ git stack diff
  # Shows diff between step2 and step1

Push all branches in the stack:
  $ git stack push-all
  # Pushes step1, step2, step3, etc. to remote

============================================================================
USER JOURNEY 7: Completing and Cleaning Up a Stack
============================================================================
After feature/step1 is merged to main:

  $ git checkout main
  $ git pull
  $ git stack delete feature/step1
  # Deletes step1 and updates step2's base to point to main
  # Then triggers sync to rebase step2 and its dependents onto main

Or manually update the base:
  $ git checkout feature/step2
  $ git stack base main
  $ git stack sync-up

============================================================================
METADATA STORAGE
============================================================================
Stack relationships are stored in git config:
  git config branch.<branch>.stackbase <base-branch>

Example:
  git config branch.feature/step2.stackbase feature/step1

============================================================================
DEVELOPMENT
============================================================================

Check syntax with:
  python3 -m py_compile /Users/y.ershov/bin/git-stack && echo "Syntax OK"

============================================================================
"""

import os
